Challenge: Implement Semantic Landmarks in Page Listing Detail

05
On this page
  1. 🛠️ Solution: Implement Semantic Landmarks in Page Listing Detail
    1. A Note About aside
    2. Adding Landmark Elements to the Listing Detail Page
    3. A Note about section
    4. Updated Code Outline

Recall from earlier in this lesson that often times more landmarks are nested inside of main.

Now it’s your turn to determine where the Listing Detail page would benefit from switching to more semantic elements.

Check out the MDN HTML elements reference and look for candidates that you think would help to better structure the content on the Listing Detail page.

🛠️ Solution: Implement Semantic Landmarks in Page Listing Detail

A Note About aside

Before we look at how to change the markup, there is an important note to be made about aside in case you chose it as one of the semantic elements in your solution.

It’s an accessibility best practice for the aside landmark element to be at top-level. In other words, it should be a sibling of main rather than nested inside of it.

More often than not, the semantic structure we add will be inside of main, so it’s usually best to choose something other than aside for page content.

Adding Landmark Elements to the Listing Detail Page

Let’s start at the top and work our way down.

Here’s an outline of the starting point of our code:

// components/page-listing-detail.js
const Listing = props => {
  const data = ListingsData.listings[props.id]
  const headerImageUrl = LoadedImageUrl(imageURLs, data.detailHeaderImageSrc)
  return (
    <BodyClassName className="header-overlap page-listing-detail">
      <>
        <HeaderPortal>
          <h1 className="visually-hidden">Camp Spots - {data.listingName}</h1>
        </HeaderPortal>
        <div>
          <div
            className="page-header"
            style={{backgroundImage: `url(${headerImageUrl}`}}
          >
            <div className="page-header-content wide-layout">
              <h2 className="listing-name">{data.listingName}</h2>
              <p className="location">{data.location}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div className="wide-layout two-parts-70-30">
            <div>
             ...
          </div>
        </div>
      </>
    </BodyClassName>
  )
}
// components/page-listing-detail.js

  const data = ListingsData.listings[props.id]
  const headerImageUrl = LoadedImageUrl(imageURLs, data.detailHeaderImageSrc)

            <div>

        </div>
      </>
    </BodyClassName>

We’ve already discussed the HeaderPortal component, so we don’t need to do anything there.

Below the portal is a div that wraps most of the page content. This could be swapped out to use an over-arching section element or perhaps a standalone article.

The div with a class of page-header could use the header element. This would add semantic structure to page, even though it won’t have as much impact on Assistive Technology as a header at the top level.

The div that wraps the H3 headings could work as a section, as would the Image Gallery div.

A Note about section

In some ways, section is the new div– it’s become overused in markup and won’t necessarily be announced in a screen reader by default as a result.

To get the most out of the section element, we need to add an accessible name that will add it to the document outline and identify this particular section in Assistive Technology. We can use an aria-label with an arbitrary string or an aria-labelledby attribute pointing to an ID on another element to accomplish this.

For our example, we’ll add an aria-label with “Site description and booking calendar” to our first section, and another with “Image Gallery” for the second.

Updated Code Outline

Here’s an outline of what the code looks like after these changes (with the full file available in the exercise1 directory).

<BodyClassName className="header-overlap page-listing-detail">
    <>
        <HeaderPortal>
            <h1 className="visually-hidden">Camp Spots</h1>
        </HeaderPortal>
        <article>
            <header className="page-header" style={{backgroundImage: `url(${headerImageUrl}`}}>
                ...
            </header>
            <section className="wide-layout two-parts-70-30" aria-label="Site description and booking calendar">
                ...
            </section>
            <section className="wide-layout" aria-label="Image gallery">
                ...
            </section>
        </article>
    </>
</BodyClassName>
<BodyClassName className="header-overlap page-listing-detail">
    <>
        <HeaderPortal>
            <h1 className="visually-hidden">Camp Spots</h1>
        </HeaderPortal>
        <article>
            <header className="page-header" style={{backgroundImage: `url(${headerImageUrl}`}}>
                ...
            </header>

                ...
            </section>

                ...
            </section>
        </article>
    </>
</BodyClassName>
